'''Joe Nalo''' (born 1951) is an artist from [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=Papua>{{cite book | last =Cochrane | first =Susan | authorlink = | last2 =Mel | first2 =Michael A.| authorlink2 = |title =Contemporary Art in Papua New Guinea| publisher =Craftsman House | series = | volume = | edition = | date =1997 | location = | pages = 57–59| language = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=YKZPAAAAMAAJ&q=Joe+Nalo&dq=Joe+Nalo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiU7rSmtP7VAhWqxlQKHf7cCQ4Q6AEIUjAJ | doi = | id = | isbn =9789057032318| mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> Nalo is a painter, printmaker, art teacher and curator.<ref name=CFAA>{{cite web | url =http://www.printsandprintmaking.gov.au/artists/7434/ | title =Joe Nalo | last = | first = | date = | website =Australian Prints + Printmaking | publisher =Centre for Australian Art| access-date =August 30, 2017 | quote = }}</ref> He was the first curator for contemporary art at the National Museum and Art Gallery of Papua New Guinea.<ref>{{cite book | last =Stanley | first = Nick| authorlink = | title =The Future of Indigenous Museums: Perspectives from the Southwest Pacific| publisher =Berghahn Books| series = | volume = | edition = | date =2007 | location = | pages =211 | language = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=BWajAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA211&dq=Joe+Nalo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiU7rSmtP7VAhWqxlQKHf7cCQ4Q6AEISDAH#v=onepage&q=Joe%20Nalo&f=false| doi = | id = | isbn =9780857455727 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> Nalo has been described in the journal ''Pacific Arts'' as "one of the best contemporary artists" in Papua New Guinea.<ref>{{cite book | last = | first = | authorlink = | title =Pacific Arts: The Journal of the Pacific Arts Association | publisher = | series = | volume = | edition =Number 25 | date = 2002| location = | pages =91, 94 | language = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=2PflAAAAIAAJ&q=joe%2Bnalo&dq=joe%2Bnalo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJ2szCjYDWAhWIqFQKHSu5Dj8Q6AEILzAC | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>
==Biography== Nalo was born in on Johnson Island in the [[Admiralty Islands]] in [[Manus Province]], Papua, New Guinea.<ref name=CFAA/> Whilst at school, Nalo won the Carriapa Art Shield.<ref name=Papua /> After graduating from teachers college he taught expressive arts and other subjects at Wau International Primary School. From 1970 to 1972 he was headmaster of Salamaua Boarding School and during this period continued to study art privately with artist Lucy Walker.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.es/books?redir_esc=y&hl=es&id=k23lAAAAIAAJ&dq=lucy+walker+joe+nalo&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=lucy+walker|title=Bung wantaim: the role of the National Arts School in creating national culture and identity in Papua New Guinea|last=Rosi|first=Pamela Christine|date=1994|publisher=Bryn Mawr College|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=432}}</ref> Nalo had already received several painting commissions when he was offered a scholarship in 1974 to study the Creative Arts Centre in Port Moresby and later went on to teach at the National Arts School as well as a professional artist. In 1975, Nalo represented Papua New Guinea at the 10th World Crafts Conference in Montreal, Canada. He travelled with Jakupa to Stuttgart, Germany in 1979 where their art was featured in an exhibition of contemporary Papua New Guinean art held in association with the 9th occasions since 1976. Nalo became a full time artist in 1991. He did his Primary Education at Kalalo Community School 1975, and then attended Siassi High School 1979. His talent was noticed by the Expressive Arts teacher and was encouraged to pursue studies in the arts.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
In 2007, Nalo was cited as an authority on the symbolism of traditional New Guinea carvings in a book published by the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref>{{cite book | last =Kjellgren | first =Eric | authorlink = | title =Oceania: Art of the Pacific Islands in the Metropolitan Museum of Art | publisher =[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] | series = | volume = | edition = | date =2007 | location = | pages =109 | language = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=_tnC5UxkeukC&pg=PA109&lpg=PA109&dq=joe+nalo+artist&source=bl&ots=DXcAMpf82Q&sig=1uwHXTQt70NMcZJG6W-ALQ7RyV4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwih-tCyz4DWAhXCzVQKHX5rAqw4ChDoAQgrMAA#v=onepage&q=joe%20nalo%20artist&f=false | doi = | id = | isbn =9781588392381| mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>
In 2008, his work was included as part of an exhibit called "Altogether: Contemporary Papua New Guinea Art" at the [[East–West Center]] in [[Honolulu]].<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.eastwestcenter.org/news-center/news-releases/altogether-contemporary-papua-new-guinea-art | title =Altogether: Contemporary Papua New Guinea Art| last = | first = | date = 2008| website =[[East–West Center]] | publisher = | access-date =August 30, 2017 | quote =Papua New Guinea’s independence from Australia in 1975 marked the explosion of a contemporary art movement through which artists explored the visual interpretation of nationalism in this new country of more than 6 million people, which occupies the eastern half of New Guinea, the second largest island in the world. Artists began to conceptualize a new national identity through their art, illustrating what it meant to be a Papua New Guinean as opposed to a clan member. }}</ref>
In 2009, Nalo was one of the artists whose work was shown at the first comprehensive exhibition of Melanesian art in [[Auckland, New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.pacificarts.org/node/256 | title =SPIRIT of the PEOPLE - New Melanesian Art: An exhibition of contemporary art from Fiji, Papua New Guinea, New Caledonia, Solomon Islands & Vanuatu | last = | first = | date = 2009| website =Pacific Arts Center | publisher = | access-date =August 30, 2017| quote = }}</ref>
